{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502066"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1822"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.39,0.14,0.02,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109484"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1822"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3670"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40841"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43854"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109484"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of profuse watery diarrhoea and cramping abdominal pain. He underwent laparoscopic appendicectomy two weeks ago for perforated appendicitis, complicated by 100 mL of purulent peritoneal fluid. He completed three days of intravenous piperacillin-tazobactam in hospital followed by oral amoxicillin-clavulanate, which he finished yesterday. He has no significant medical history and takes pantoprazole for post-operative reflux symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 112/min, blood pressure 115/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is diffusely tender without peritonism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ewhite cell count 18 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ecreatinine 150 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Ealbumin 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral metronidazole","Oral vancomycin","Intravenous metronidazole","Oral fidaxomicin","Combined oral vancomycin and intravenous metronidazole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of severe \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection following broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy. Severe disease is defined by white cell count \u0026gt;15 \u00d7 10\u2079/L, fever \u226538.5\u00b0C, severe abdominal pain, albumin \u0026lt;25 g/L, or pseudomembranous colitis on endoscopy. This patient meets criteria with leucocytosis (18 \u00d7 10\u2079/L) and fever (38.5\u00b0C). Recent surgery, hospitalisation, antibiotic exposure and proton pump inhibitor use are all risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended first-line treatment for severe \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection due to superior cure rates and reduced treatment failure compared to metronidazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended as first-line therapy for severe disease due to inferior outcomes. It may be used for mild cases in settings where vancomycin is unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate as it does not achieve sufficient intraluminal concentrations in the colon. While it may play a role in severe, complicated diseases, it should not be used as monotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral fidaxomicin\u003C/strong\u003E is as effective as vancomycin for initial treatment but is significantly more expensive. It may be preferred for recurrent episodes due to lower recurrence rates, but is not typically used first-line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral vancomycin and intravenous metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe complicated disease, defined as \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection with sepsis or septic shock, ileus, perforated viscus, or toxic megacolon, which are not present in this case. Another indication is fulminant (rapidly progressing severe) disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clostridioides difficile infection commonly occurs following broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy, with highest risk during or within four weeks of treatment.","Severe Clostridioides difficile infection is defined by white cell count \u003E15 \u00d7 10\u2079/L, fever \u226538.5\u00b0C, severe abdominal pain, albumin \u003C25 g/L, or pseudomembranous colitis.","Oral vancomycin is the first-line treatment for severe Clostridioides difficile infection"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Clostridioides difficile infection. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2024 [cited 2025 Jul 21]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"da